  "passageParts": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "Thinner isn't always better.A number of studies have\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthat normal-weight people are in fact at higher risk of some diseases compared to those who are overweight. And there are health conditions for which being overweight is actually\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.For example,heavier women are less likely to develop calcium deficiency than thin women.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\namong the elderly, being somewhat overweight is often an\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nof good health.\n Of even greater\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nis the fact that obesity turns out to be very difficult to define.It is often defined\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nbody mass index, or BMI. BMI\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nbody mass divided by the square of height. An adult with a BMI of 18 to 25 is often considered to be normal weight. Between 25 and 30 is overweight. And over 30 is considered obese. Obesity,\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 8
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​, can be divided into moderately obese,severely obese,and very severely obese.\n While such numerical standards seem\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 9
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​,they are not. Obesity is probably less a matter of weight than body fat. Some people with a high BMI are in fact extremely fit,\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 10
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nothers with a low BMI may be in poor\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 11
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.For example, many collegiate and professional football players\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 12
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nas obese, though their percentage body fat is low. Conversely, someone with a small frame may have high body fat but a\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 13
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nBMI.\n Today we have a(an)\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 14
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto label obesity as a disgrace.The overweight are sometimes\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nin the media with their faces covered. Stereotypes\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 16
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nwith obesity include laziness, lack of will power, and lower prospects for success. Teachers, employers, and health professionals have been shown to harbor biases against the obese.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nvery young children tend to look down on the overweight,and teasing about body build has long been a problem in schools.\n Negative attitudes toward obesity, _"
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "in health concerns, have stimulated a number of anti-obesity"
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "_.My own hospital system has banned sugary drinks from its facilities. Many employers have instituted weight loss and fitness initiatives. Michelle Obama launched a high-visibility campaign "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "_ childhood obesity, even claiming that it represents our greatest national security threat."
    }
  ],
